
Golden rule: pull before you push. Always grab the latest version before uploading your work it saves everyone from merge nightmares.


THE DAILY FLOW

pull
write code
add
commit
push


GETTING THE REPO (ONCE, ON DAY ONE)

1. git clone https://github.com/Rhooba/Cuesta-Cougors.git
Downloads the whole project to your computer. Only do this once.

2. cd repo
Step into the folder that was just created.



PULLING GRAB EVERYONE'S LATEST CHANGES

1. git pull origin main
Downloads and merges the latest from the main branch. Run this every time you sit down to work.




PUSHING/SEND YOUR WORK TO GITHUB

1. git add .
Stages everything you changed. The dot means "all files." You can also do git add Driver.java for one file.

2. git commit -m "add Driver.addRating() method" (example)
Saves a snapshot with a message. Be specific â€” future you will thank present you.

3. git push origin main
Uploads your commit to GitHub so everyone can see it.



BRANCHES WORK WITHOUT WRECKING MAIN

Create and switch to a new branch
1. git checkout -b feature/driver
Makes a new branch and jumps to it. Name it after what you're building.

2. git push origin feature/driver
Push your branch up so others can see it too.


Switch between branches
1. git branch
Lists all branches. The one with a star is where you are right now.

2. git checkout main
Jumps back to main. Swap "main" for any branch name.



MERGING YOUR BRANCH INTO MAIN (WHEN YOU'RE DONE)

1. git checkout main
Switch back to main first.

2. git pull origin main
Grab any updates your teammates pushed while you were working.

3. git merge feature/driver
Brings your branch's changes into main.

4. git push origin main
Push the merged result up to GitHub.



USEFUL ANYTIME

? git status 
Shows what you've changed and what's staged. Run this whenever you're confused.

? git log --oneline
Shows recent commits in a clean list. Good for seeing what everyone has done.
